  <p class="title">Watch Out: AI Generated Tax Scams Can Look A Lot Like They Came From The IRS</p>
  <div class="story">
   <p>It was a typical day for Sarah, a small business owner in Ohio. She was going through her work emails when she noticed an email from the IRS. Her heart started racing as she read through the email, which stated she had underreported her income and owed a large sum of money in taxes.</p>
   <p>Panicked, Sarah immediately called the number provided in the email. A man claiming to be from the IRS answered and demanded that she pay the balance immediately. Sarah, not wanting to get in trouble with the IRS, quickly paid the balance. It wasn't until later that she realized she had fallen for an AI generated tax scam.</p>
   <p>Unfortunately, Sarah's story is not a unique one. In fact, AI generated tax scams are becoming increasingly common and sophisticated, making it harder for individuals to distinguish between a legitimate communication from the IRS and a fake one.</p>
   <p>According to a report by the IRS, tax scams are the number one consumer fraud scam, with more than $26 billion lost to tax scams between 2014 and 2020. As such, it is crucial that individuals and businesses alike remain vigilant when it comes to tax scams.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="examples">
   <p>Here are some quantifiable examples of the impact of AI generated tax scams:</p>
   <ul>
    <li>In 2020, the IRS issued a warning about an increase in phishing scams, stating that it had already seen a 350% increase in phishing schemes compared to the previous year.</li>
    <li>In early 2021, the IRS reported a new tax evasion scheme in which scammers were offering to purchase taxpayers' EINs, which allows them to create fake W-2s and file fraudulent tax returns.</li>
    <li>A recent report by the Better Business Bureau found that the average loss for victims of tax scams in 2020 was $5,000.</li>
   </ul>
  </div>
  <p class="tips">Tips for avoiding AI generated tax scams:</p>
  <div class="tips-list">
   <ol>
    <li>Never give out personal or financial information over the phone or through email unless you are absolutely certain it's a legitimate communication.</li>
    <li>Be wary of any unexpected emails or calls from the IRS, especially if they demand immediate payment or threaten legal action if you don't comply. The IRS typically communicates through mail first and will never threaten to arrest or deport you.</li>
    <li>Stay up to date on the latest tax scams by regularly checking the IRS's website or subscribing to its newsletter.</li>
   </ol>
  </div>
  <div class="conclusion">
   <p>In summary, AI generated tax scams are a serious threat that can leave individuals and businesses financially vulnerable. To protect yourself, it is essential to remain vigilant and stay informed of the latest tax scams and warning signs. By following these tips, you can avoid falling victim to these sophisticated scams and keep your finances and personal information secure.</p>
  </div>
